Palestine responds to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas said Thursday at a session of the UN General Assembly that he would break any agreements he made with Israel if the country's future government tried to comply with Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement of the annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
"If the future Israeli government, as it emerges, proceeds to implement this plan, we will nullify all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made," he said.
"We will reject the whole plan completely and completely," Abbas threatened with pressure.
"It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means - little matter what the consequences will be - by fully engaging in the application of international law and in the fight against terrorism," said the President of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, Israel's former prime minister, was again given the mission to form a government after the September 17 election.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won it, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and intend to include all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank in Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by Yasser Arafat at the time, signed a number of peace agreements that the United States patronized.
The 84-year-old Abbas also promised to hold a general election in Palestinian lands during the session of the UN General Assembly.
The last took place in 2006.
"After returning to the country, I will convene local elections in the West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem and all those who would oppose them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community," the Palestinian president declared solemnly.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the United Nations, to exercise the powers vested in the "full-fledged members of the United Nations and all its organs and institutions."
The Palestinian leader concluded the speech with a call to the international community to "force Israel to comply with all the United Nations provisions."
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas' speech, stating that the Palestinian leader "would rather focus at the UN on the Palestinian Authority's efforts against Israel than fight against calls for terrorism in the Autonomy under his leadership."
Danon, however, as the agencies note, did not refer to Netanyahu's announced annexation of occupied Palestinian lands.
