105 million PLN for video game companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced on Friday the results of the third edition of the GameINN program.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by NCBR were the development of a platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine that creates a map of the real world together with an application that allows users to transfer data; a test and training platform for verifying practical skills at the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using a novel model of gameplay based on the interaction of the virtual world with the virtual industry.
The objective of the GameINN sector program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game producers sector on the global market by 2023.
According to the NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 was PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 was PLN 2.23 billion.
"GameINN's specially prepared research agenda and already reaching PLN 300 million support for entrepreneurs under this sector program provide a significant impetus for the further, dynamic growth of the Polish gamedev", reads the release.
The video game industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential we have in Poland.
"The incentives introduced by the government for innovation-oriented entrepreneurs, such as R&D reliefs, competence improvement programs, IP box or support programs implemented by the NCBR, drive the innovative activities of companies and allow them to compete more effectively in a very competitive market," said Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the release.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project funding, but also stays in their pockets – three-quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R&D relief in 2018 than the year before.
"The amount of deductible costs related to R&D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which gave over PLN 300 million of savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in the three editions of GameINN," emphasises the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of NCBR Dr. Wojciech Kamieniecki recalls that in the two previous grant competitions with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million, 78 innovative projects were awarded.
The huge interest in the 3rd competition and the variety of applications submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
"It is particularly gratifying that among the selected projects – as in previous editions – there are projects on solutions for not only entertainment, but also related to Industry 4.0," he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, consortia of entrepreneurs and consortia of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for the total amount of funding of approximately PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million in funding.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available at ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sector program is implemented as part of the Intelligent Development Operational Program.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Agreement, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team or 11 bit studios.
