These trees may completely disappear from Europe
"42 percent of the tree species that make up Europe's stand are at risk," warns the International Union for the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in its "Red Book of European Trees" published on Friday.
At the top of the list are, among others, chestnuts and rowanberry.
The IUCN, an organization based in Gland, Switzerland, publishes a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was compiled by specialists who, based on research, concluded that of the 454 tree species found in Europe (as well as elsewhere in the world), 42% are "highly endangered".
Among the causes, the Red Book lists rapid urban agglomeration growth and global climate change.
However, the most endangered are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
When it comes to typically European tree stands, according to IUCN specialists, 58% of species are at risk, and 15 percent, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are at risk of extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Book lists errors in the operation of the stand, accelerated urbanization, too intensive logging, and, subsequently, forest fires and changes taking place in the European ecostism.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and lichens is also at great risk.
"The consequences of human activities lead to the gradual disappearance of European plant species and pose a danger in Europe of extinction of important and underappreciated varieties that form the basis of European ecosystems and affect the health of our planet," concluded Luc Bas, who heads the European office of the IUCN.
