GUS: Life is getting better in Poland
The report on household budgets published by the Central Statistical Office on Friday shows that as good or rather good its financial situation was assessed last year by as many as 44% of them.
A year earlier, this percentage was 37.2 percent, in 2016 33.5 percent, and earlier – since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of household situations – it never exceeded 30 percent.
He considered a total of 8.1% of households to be bad or rather bad in his financial situation last year, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and more than 20 percent in 2009.
The material situation of households of self-employed workers is the best.
In this group, over 70% of respondents consider it to be good or rather good.
At the other pole are the pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The subjective assessment of the material situation of households is also heavily influenced by the number of children.
The worst is for single parents, of whom a good or rather good financial situation is declared by 32 percent.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 percent, and among childless households it is 48.8%.
In these statistics, the effect of the 500+ program is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst of its material situation was assessed by single parents raising offspring and large families (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid increase in income, primarily from work.
However, that is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, at the level of the voivodships there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best grades are formulated by residents of the Opole Voivodeship, where 48.9 percent of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
There are further Lubusz Voivodeships (47.7 percent), Silesian Voivodeships (47.6 percent), Mazovian Voivodeships (47.3 percent) and West Pomeranian Voivodeships (47.1 percent).
Meanwhile, in Opole, the disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) was less than 94% of the national average last year, and in Lubusk, it was 98%.
The highest incomes were held by residents of Mazovian (120 percent of the national average) and Silesian (104 percent).
On average, in Poland, disposable income per person was PLN 1,693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price changes) it increased by 4.3 percent compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, this is a fairly low result.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7%, and a year later by 6.3 percent.
While income growth slows down, it also inhibits spending growth.
These per person amounted to PLN 1187 last year, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, spending per person increased in real terms by 1.9 percent, and in 2016 by 4.3 percent.
Surveys of household budgets suggest that the statistical household now spends 70.1 percent of its disposable income, while still in 2014 this share exceeded 80 percent, and by 2006 it exceeded 90 percent.
