289 MPs supported the government's motion for a recess, against 306.
Two opposition parties after the conventions
The lack of consent to the recess can be seen as the political revenge of the opposition at Prime Minister Boris Johnson for his decision to suspend parliament for five weeks (on Tuesday, the decision was declared unlawful and non-existent by the Supreme Court) and for not wanting to apologize for it after the judges' ruling.
Following this ruling, the House of Commons resumed its session on Wednesday, with the most important event of the day being Johnson's speech and the ensuing tumultuous debate.
Johnson accused the opposition of blocking Brexit and avoiding early elections.
"It's time for Brexit to come to fruition.
It must be implemented in order to respect the result of the referendum.
Brexit must come so that we can deal with the agreement on citizens' priorities, on health care, on the cost of living.
Brexit must be realized so that we can unite this country," Johnson said.
The Conservative Party conference is scheduled to start in Manchester next Sunday and run until Wednesday 2 October.
Conferences of the two main opposition groups – the Labour Party and the Liberal Democrats – have already taken place.
