"Republic": Ignoring a policeman's command will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregarding a specific behavior order issued by a police officer is to be a new type of offense, threatened with fines, arrest or restriction of freedom.
Such a change is wanted by the police unionists.
The idea went to the Parliamentary Committee on Petitions.
"The case is serious, because already every year more than half a million misdemeanor cases go to Polish courts," the statement read.
The "Rzeczpospolita" determined that the petition which the Independent Policemen's Trade Union writes to MPs on the amendment of the Code of Offences has a chance of success.
The petitioners propose a new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Misdemeanors.
It would read: "He who does not comply with the demand or command of a public officer, issued within the limits and under the provisions of the Act, shall be subject to the penalty of arrest, fine or restriction of liberty."
"Par. 3 of this provision speaks of an identical punishment for those who, by not following orders, will prevent or hinder the performance of the official act," the journal says.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski told Rzeczpospolita that although he agrees with the main message of the recipe proposal, he fears that if it is implemented, it can be used in matters of political manifestation.
"In situations of freedom demonstrations, this would be unfavourable and instead of mitigating the situation, they would exacerbate it," he adds.
Statistics released by the newspaper show that 86% of citizens gave a positive assessment of police interventions in 2018 and that every month, the services undertake 1.5 million interventions in the city.
Buras worries about Europe
Ichym Topol's writing is in his blood.
Among his ancestors are editors, translators, writers.
Father, Josef Topol, was one of the most important post-war Czech playwrights, today exchanged in a single row with Vaclav Havel.
Thus, the curse of talent, which this one seeks to exploit, hung over J'chym from the beginning.
After eight years, he returned with a "Sensitive Man".
The protagonists are Buras and Soca along with two sons, who, however, do not form a typical Czech family.
They are travelling actors, travelling around Europe.
He's a Shakespearean lover and a thief, she's a one-eyed translator who doesn't part with a bottle of wine.
One of the boys from birth made no sound of himself, and for the other time stopped in infancy.
But it is not the heroes who are the most important in this story.
All of them are merely a backdrop for observing a world in which there is no longer room for artistic nomads.
It's a world of clogged provinces, a society of old, suspicious people, and promiscuous youth.
The "sensitive man" in places turns into an absurd theatrical.
The narrative mimics the didascalia, and the characters' conversations create this world.
The scene is a Europe full of fears for its future, but also constant questions about the past.
Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancels 105 flights due to bankruptcy Thomas Cook
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has fallen, its Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is in operation.
However, the company has problems.
Brussels Airlines has announced that it will cancel 105 flights in October due to problems with bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All trips with an office that has been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The Ghent court also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian subsidiaries: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, about 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased at Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were expected to leave the office by the end of the year.
As late as Monday, spokeswoman Thomas Cook Belgium Leen Segers said the company is now "fully operational" despite the bankruptcy of the British parent company, which has caused concern among employees and customers.
The office then reassured that the customers who bought the tours in it would go on vacation.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – declared bankruptcy on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The immediate cause of the bankruptcy was the collapse of last-chance talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
Creditors demanded that, in addition to the 900 million-pound rescue plan already agreed in August, the company obtain an additional 200 million as collateral for the winter period, when travel agencies usually have lower turnover.
However, the company's problems had been building up for several years, resulting in a debt of up to 1.6 billion pounds.
