Goerlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for reviews
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an unusual offer was prepared for the German visitors by the Gérlitz.
The actions are intended to help fight the progressive decline in the city's population.
Goerlitz is the easternmost city in Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140,000 tourists annually.
However, according to The Guardian, the city is facing significant problems.
The lowest wages in Germany are found in Goerlitz.
The city is also struggling with a steady decline in population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left for the west of the country, which translated into a 25 percent decline in the city's population.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000 people.
In order to combat the depopulation, officials came up with the idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been submitted to the program.
Two thirds of them were made by residents of large cities.
The programme was also attended by people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
"When we applied, we thought that the program was supposed to convince people to move to Gorlitz," one of the project participants said.
"Now we feel it doesn't matter if we stay here after four weeks or not," he added.
The city has seven thousand vacant apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the national average.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main goal of the program is to get feedback from the participants of the program.
The information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revive smaller German cities.
"We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move – what their motivation was," said Robert Knippschild, program manager.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas for attracting new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals to live and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in American Tulsa, Oklahoma.
